# .trivyignore — waivers for Trivy findings you have reviewed and accepted.
#
# Add one CVE ID per line. Comments above the ID are part of the file's git
# history and become your audit trail for why a finding is not being fixed.
# A waiver without a reason is just a mute button, not evidence.
#
# Convention: each block records the attack vector, where the dep lives in
# uptime-kuma, why the exploit prerequisite is not met, and a 2026-11 /
# next-louislam-bump revisit trigger. Same pattern as mirror-Plausible.

# ============================================================================
# npm-layer findings (uptime-kuma's package-lock.json, mirrored verbatim)
# ============================================================================

# CVE-2026-22029 was the react-router XSS in mirror-Plausible — not present
# here (uptime-kuma uses Vue, not React). No waiver needed.

# CVE-2026-26996, CVE-2026-27903, CVE-2026-27904 — minimatch ReDoS family
# (each HIGH, CVSS 7.5, DoS only).
# Fixes spread across minimatch branches; floor for all three is 3.1.4.
# uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pulls minimatch 9.0.3 transitively through eslint /
# archiver-utils / readdir-glob / glob — all dev-time or build-time.
#
# Exploit prerequisite for the entire family: the GLOB PATTERN itself must
# be attacker-controlled. uptime-kuma's call sites feed minimatch only with
# hardcoded patterns from the maintainer's source; no untrusted-pattern
# code path exists.
#
# Impact class: process hang in the CI build runner if exploited (which
# requires upstream-source-write privilege). Not reachable at runtime by
# any image consumer.
#
# Revisit when louislam bumps the dev-tool transitive chain, or by 2026-11
# — whichever first.
CVE-2026-26996
CVE-2026-27903
CVE-2026-27904

# CVE-2026-33671 — picomatch ReDoS via crafted extglob patterns
# (HIGH, CVSS 7.5, DoS only). Fix in picomatch 4.0.4.
# uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pulls picomatch 4.0.3 transitively via chokidar and the
# eslint ecosystem.
#
# Same shape as the minimatch family: requires attacker-controlled glob
# pattern. Not reachable in uptime-kuma's call sites (chokidar watch globs
# in compile.js are hardcoded; eslint patterns come from the maintainer's
# config).
#
# Revisit when louislam bumps chokidar / eslint / rollup, or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-33671

# CVE-2025-64756 — glob CLI command injection (HIGH, CVSS 7.5).
# Fix in glob 10.5.0+ / 11.1.0. uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pulls glob 10.3.16 and
# 7.2.3 transitively.
#
# Exploit prerequisite: the `glob -c <command>` CLI form must be invoked
# with attacker-controllable filenames. Programmatic glob() API calls are
# unaffected. uptime-kuma exclusively uses the programmatic API; the CLI
# is never spawned by application code.
#
# Revisit on next louislam dep bump, or 2026-11.
CVE-2025-64756

# CVE-2026-23745, 23950, 24842, 26960, 29786, 31802 — node-tar (six CVEs,
# HIGH, archive-extraction path traversal / hardlink / symlink class).
# Fix floor: 7.5.11.
# uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pins tar 6.2.1 directly.
#
# Exploit prerequisite for the entire family: the application must call
# tar.x() / tar extraction with an attacker-controlled archive. uptime-kuma's
# only `require('tar')` sites are extra/download-dist.js (run via
# `npm run setup` at install time, downloads dist.tar.gz from GitHub
# releases) and extra/release/lib.mjs (release-tooling, never on the
# server). The runtime image (server/server.js and what it reaches) does
# not require('tar').
#
# Even the install-time reachability is gated: download-dist.js extracts
# the .tar.gz served by GitHub releases for louislam/uptime-kuma. A
# compromise of those releases would already be a supply-chain class
# outside of this CVE's scope.
#
# Revisit when louislam bumps tar (likely on 2.4.x), or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-23745
CVE-2026-23950
CVE-2026-24842
CVE-2026-26960
CVE-2026-29786
CVE-2026-31802

# CVE-2026-25128, CVE-2026-25896 (CRIT 9.3), CVE-2026-26278, CVE-2026-33036
# — fast-xml-parser (four CVEs, fix floor 5.5.6).
# uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pulls fast-xml-parser 5.2.5 transitively via gamedig
# (server/monitor-types/gamedig.js queries game servers; some game
# protocols return XML, parsed by fxp).
#
# Exploit prerequisite: an attacker-controlled XML response from a game
# server that uptime-kuma is configured to monitor — a malicious response
# triggers admin-XSS (25896) or backend-DoS (25128/26278/33036).
#
# Waived for THIS deployment because the gamedig monitor type is not used.
# server/monitor-types/gamedig.js is dead code in our setup; fast-xml-parser
# is loaded into the require-graph but never invoked. If a gamedig monitor
# is ever added, this waiver MUST be revisited (revert this section to the
# commented-out form and rebuild) — the CVEs are real and reachable as
# soon as the monitor is configured.
#
# Revisit immediately if a gamedig monitor is added, when louislam bumps
# fast-xml-parser to >= 5.5.6, or by 2026-11 — whichever first.
CVE-2026-25128
CVE-2026-25896
CVE-2026-26278
CVE-2026-33036

# CVE-2026-41242 (CRITICAL, CVSS 9.8) — protobufjs arbitrary code execution
# via "type" field in .proto definitions. Fix in protobufjs 7.5.5 / 8.0.1.
# uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pins protobufjs ~7.2.6 directly.
#
# Reachability: server/monitor-types/grpc.js loads .proto definitions
# supplied by the user via the gRPC-monitor configuration UI, then decodes
# gRPC responses against them. A malicious .proto pasted into a monitor
# config triggers arbitrary code execution in the Node.js process at next
# poll — admin → server-RCE in the container.
#
# Waived for THIS deployment because the gRPC monitor type is not used.
# server/monitor-types/grpc.js and the protobufjs decode path are
# unreachable in our setup. If a gRPC monitor is ever added, this waiver
# MUST be revisited (revert this section to the commented-out form and
# rebuild) — the RCE is real and triggers on the first poll of any
# attacker-controlled .proto.
#
# Revisit immediately if a gRPC monitor is added, when louislam bumps
# protobufjs to >= 7.5.5, or by 2026-11 — whichever first.
CVE-2026-41242

# CVE-2026-44289, CVE-2026-44290, CVE-2026-44291, CVE-2026-44293 — protobufjs
# follow-on family disclosed 2026-05 alongside the upstream 7.5.6 / 8.0.2
# patch release. Same library, same call-site, same reachability story as
# CVE-2026-41242 above — waived for the same reason and tracked as one unit
# so the next louislam bump closes them all together.
#
# Severities and shapes:
#   - CVE-2026-44289 (HIGH, CVSS 7.5) — DoS via unbounded protobuf message
#     recursion during decode. Attacker-supplied wire bytes with deeply
#     nested submessages cause stack exhaustion / event-loop stall.
#   - CVE-2026-44290 (HIGH, CVSS 7.5) — process-wide DoS through unsafe
#     option-path traversal. Crafted option strings in a .proto definition
#     trigger pathological resolution.
#   - CVE-2026-44291 (HIGH, CVSS 8.1) — code-generation gadget reachable
#     after prototype pollution: if an attacker can first pollute
#     Object.prototype (separate primitive), protobufjs's generated decoder
#     becomes an RCE sink. Pre-condition required, but chained with any
#     prototype-pollution gadget in the dep tree this is server-RCE.
#   - CVE-2026-44293 (HIGH, CVSS 8.1) — code injection via attacker-
#     controlled `bytes` field default values flowing into generated
#     toObject() code. Triggered when decoding a message whose .proto
#     definition contains a malicious default.
#
# Fix floor for all four: protobufjs 7.5.6 / 8.0.2. uptime-kuma 2.3.2 pins
# `"protobufjs": "~7.2.6"` in its top-level package.json (verified against
# louislam/uptime-kuma@2.3.2 — direct dependency of the server runtime,
# not transitive). The tilde range allows only 7.2.x; a rebuild on top of
# the same upstream tag resolves to 7.2.6 again. Closing these CVEs at the
# library level therefore REQUIRES an upstream uptime-kuma release that
# bumps the constraint. No combination of base-image bump, npm cache
# refresh, or override patch on our side can resolve them — patching
# package.json downstream would mean carrying a runtime-code fork, which
# violates this repo's "build-system fork only, no source-code fork"
# invariant (see oss-mirror-build/README.md positioning section).
#
# Reachability in THIS deployment (single load-bearing argument, shared
# across all four CVE shapes):
#
#   protobufjs is imported by exactly one runtime call site in the
#   uptime-kuma server: server/monitor-types/grpc.js. That module loads a
#   user-supplied .proto definition from the gRPC-monitor configuration
#   UI and decodes incoming gRPC responses against it. Every one of these
#   four CVEs needs that exact call path to fire:
#     - 44289 / 44293 trigger on decode() of attacker-shaped wire bytes
#       (44289) or .proto defaults (44293) — gRPC monitor active.
#     - 44290 triggers on .proto option parsing — gRPC monitor active.
#     - 44291 triggers on the generated decoder running against a
#       prototype-polluted Object.prototype — gRPC monitor active AND a
#       prior prototype-pollution primitive, both gated behind admin-only
#       monitor configuration.
#
#   We do NOT use the gRPC monitor type in any deployment of this image.
#   server/monitor-types/grpc.js is present in the require graph (loaded
#   by the monitor-type registry at boot) but its decode pathway is never
#   invoked because no monitor instance of that type is configured in our
#   uptime-kuma databases. The vulnerable protobufjs functions are
#   statically present but dynamically unreachable.
#
#   Defence-in-depth: even if a gRPC monitor were added, the .proto
#   definition is admin-supplied via the authenticated uptime-kuma UI. An
#   unauthenticated remote attacker cannot reach the decode path without
#   first compromising an admin account, at which point server RCE is
#   already trivially available through other monitor types (e.g., the
#   shell-script monitor). The CVEs would convert an admin into a
#   slightly faster RCE, not introduce a new privilege boundary.
#
# Risk acceptance: zero exposure for this image in its configured use as
# our internal uptime monitor. Logged here, not silently muted, so the
# next reviewer sees both the shape of the CVEs and the exact precondition
# that would invalidate the waiver.
#
# Revisit triggers (any one reverts the waiver):
#   1. A gRPC monitor is added to any uptime-kuma instance running this
#      image — revert IMMEDIATELY, do not wait for the calendar trigger.
#      CVE-2026-44291's RCE shape in particular makes this non-optional.
#   2. louislam publishes an uptime-kuma release that bumps protobufjs to
#      >= 7.5.6 (likely 2.4.0 or a 2.3.x patch) — clear all four lines
#      and rebuild.
#   3. Calendar fallback: 2026-11 — re-examine even if neither 1 nor 2
#      has happened, in case the threat model has shifted.
CVE-2026-44289
CVE-2026-44290
CVE-2026-44291
CVE-2026-44293

# CVE-2026-4800 — lodash _.template imports key injection (HIGH, CVSS 8.1).
# Fix in lodash 4.18.0+. uptime-kuma 2.3.0 pulls lodash 4.17.23
# transitively via redbean-node (the SQLite ORM).
#
# Exploit prerequisite: application calls _.template(..., { imports: {
# ATTACKER_CONTROLLED_KEY: ... } }). redbean-node uses lodash for utility
# functions, never for template rendering. _.template is not invoked
# anywhere in the uptime-kuma server runtime.
#
# Revisit when redbean-node bumps lodash (already done in 4.18.0; awaiting
# upstream redbean-node release), or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-4800

# CVE-2026-44665 — fast-xml-builder@1.1.5 attribute-quote bypass (HIGH).
# Fix in fast-xml-builder 1.1.7. uptime-kuma 2.3.2 pulls 1.1.5 transitively:
#
#   mongodb (optionalDependencies)
#    -> @aws-sdk/credential-providers
#        -> @aws-sdk/core
#            -> @aws-sdk/xml-builder
#                -> fast-xml-parser
#                    -> fast-xml-builder
#
# Three independent reasons the CVE is unreachable in this image:
#  1. Optional path: the @aws-sdk chain only loads when a MongoDB monitor
#     is configured with AWS-IAM auth (MongoDB Atlas). Not used here.
#  2. Wrong protocol class: @aws-sdk/xml-builder constructs XML request
#     bodies for S3/SES/SQS/SNS. The only AWS client present in this
#     dependency chain is @aws-sdk/client-cognito-identity, which speaks
#     JSON / query-string — xml-builder is never invoked along this path.
#  3. CVE shape: it's an output-encoding bug requiring attacker-controlled
#     values to be passed as XML attribute strings in outgoing AWS
#     requests. All AWS-call inputs in uptime-kuma originate from
#     admin-supplied monitor config, not from external probe targets.
#
# Revisit when louislam bumps mongodb / fast-xml-parser, or by 2026-08-09.
CVE-2026-44665

# CVE-2026-45618 (CRITICAL, CVSS 10.0) — liquidjs template-injection RCE.
# Fix in liquidjs 10.26.0. uptime-kuma 2.3.2 pins `"liquidjs": "~10.25.0"`
# as a DIRECT dependency in its top-level package.json (verified against
# louislam/uptime-kuma@2.3.2). The tilde range allows only 10.25.x; a
# rebuild on the same upstream tag resolves back to 10.25.x, never 10.26.0.
# Closing this at the library level therefore REQUIRES an upstream uptime-
# kuma release that bumps the constraint — same situation as the protobufjs
# block above. No base-image bump, npm cache refresh, or override patch on
# our side resolves it; patching package.json downstream would be a
# runtime-code fork, violating this repo's "build-system fork only, no
# source-code fork" invariant (see oss-mirror-build/README.md).
#
# Honest reachability — this is NOT dead code like the gamedig/gRPC blocks.
# The vulnerable parse()/render() path is a live, commonly-used feature:
#
#   liquidjs is loaded by server/notification-providers/notification-
#   provider.js::renderTemplate(), called by 14 notification providers
#   (telegram, smtp, webhook, discord, slack, matrix, ntfy, ...). When a
#   notification has "Use Template" enabled, the provider passes a
#   user-authored template string (e.g. notification.telegramTemplate, or
#   the custom message body) to engine.parse() + engine.render(). The
#   CVE's valueOf-filter / Function-constructor gadget fires on parse of a
#   crafted template — engine constructor opts (relativeReference:false,
#   bogus root) do NOT block it. Trigger is the "Test" button (renders
#   immediately) or the next real notification send -> arbitrary JS in the
#   Node process = RCE in the container as the `node` user.
#
# Why we accept the risk for THIS deployment:
#  1. Injection surface is the TEMPLATE STRING only. Monitored-target data
#     (msg / monitorJSON / heartbeatJSON) flows into the render *context*,
#     not the parsed template — so there is NO SSTI from external probe
#     responses. The template is settable solely through the authenticated
#     uptime-kuma notification-config UI/API.
#  2. The template field is admin/operator-supplied. An unauthenticated
#     remote attacker cannot reach the parser. The CVSS 10.0 base score
#     assumes attacker-controlled templates with no auth, which does not
#     hold here.
#  3. Residual risk is an ESCALATION chain, not first access: an operator
#     account takeover (CSRF / XSS / credential theft) would convert a
#     session compromise into full container RCE. We accept this for our
#     single-operator internal deployment, where notification editing is
#     not exposed to lower-privileged or untrusted users.
#
# Revisit triggers (any one reverts the waiver):
#  1. Notification editing becomes reachable by non-admin / untrusted users
#     in any deployment of this image — revert IMMEDIATELY; the auth gate
#     that this waiver rests on is then gone.
#  2. louislam publishes an uptime-kuma release bumping liquidjs to
#     >= 10.26.0 (likely a 2.3.x patch or 2.4.0) — clear this line and
#     rebuild.
#  3. Calendar fallback: 2026-11.
CVE-2026-45618

# CVE-2026-45617 (HIGH) — liquidjs ReDoS via quadratic backtracking in the
# `strip_html` filter regex. Fix in liquidjs 10.26.0 — same library, same
# pin, same call-site as CVE-2026-45618 above (installed 10.25.7; the
# `~10.25.0` constraint in uptime-kuma's package.json keeps a rebuild on
# 10.25.x, so this is NOT closable by a rebuild and tracks as one unit with
# 45618 until an upstream liquidjs bump).
#
# Shape and reachability (weaker than 45618's RCE):
#  - DoS only. A pathological input string fed through the `strip_html`
#    filter causes quadratic backtracking and stalls the Node event loop.
#  - Two preconditions, both required: (a) an admin-authored notification
#    template that actually uses the `strip_html` filter — not the default
#    templates — AND (b) the filtered string is attacker-influenced. The
#    only externally-influenced values reaching the render context are
#    `msg` / fields of monitorJSON (e.g. a monitor name or status text);
#    the template itself is admin-supplied via the authenticated UI.
#  - Worst case is a single-process event-loop stall in the notification
#    send path, not RCE and not a privilege-boundary crossing.
#
# Accepted for our deployment: our notification templates do not use the
# `strip_html` filter, so the vulnerable regex is never reached. Even if it
# were, the impact ceiling is a transient DoS of the notification worker.
#
# Revisit triggers: a notification template using `strip_html` is added; or
# louislam bumps liquidjs to >= 10.26.0 (clears this together with 45618);
# or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-45617

# ============================================================================
# Go-binary findings — vendored in cloudflared (the tunnel client we install
# from Cloudflare's apt repo). cloudflared is run only when the user
# configures a Cloudflare Tunnel monitor; otherwise it sits idle in the
# image with no active code path.
# ============================================================================

# CVE-2026-25679, CVE-2026-32280, CVE-2026-32281, CVE-2026-32283 — Go stdlib
# DoS family in cloudflared's bundled Go runtime (Go 1.24.13).
# Fix: stdlib >= 1.25.9 / 1.26.2. cloudflared ships its own Go runtime; we
# can't bump it without rebuilding cloudflared from source (we don't —
# we install the .deb from pkg.cloudflare.com).
#
# Reachability in our deployment: cloudflared's TLS, x509-chain-build, and
# URL-parsing paths are exercised against Cloudflare's edge (controlled,
# trusted origin) and against Cloudflare-issued tunnel-control payloads
# (signed by Cloudflare). The DoS class CVEs all require attacker-supplied
# malformed input — which would mean a Cloudflare-edge compromise, outside
# our threat model.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb (typically every
# few weeks; check pkg.cloudflare.com), or 2026-09 — whichever first.
CVE-2026-25679
CVE-2026-32280
CVE-2026-32281
CVE-2026-32283

# CVE-2026-33186 (CRITICAL, CVSS 9.8) — google.golang.org/grpc authz bypass.
# Fix in grpc-go 1.79.3. Vendored inside cloudflared.
#
# Reachability: cloudflared's gRPC endpoints handle the tunnel-control
# protocol with Cloudflare's edge. The local-side gRPC server (if any)
# binds to a Unix socket inside the container, accessible only to the
# in-container `node` user. A network-reachable gRPC authz bypass would
# require the cloudflared edge-side or in-container access — both outside
# the remote-attacker threat model for a deployed uptime-kuma.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb, or 2026-09.
CVE-2026-33186

# CVE-2026-34986 — go-jose v4 JWE decryption DoS panic (HIGH).
# Fix in go-jose 4.1.4. Vendored inside cloudflared.
#
# Same waiver shape as the existing CVE-2026-34986 entry in mirror-Gokapi:
# the JWE-decryption codepath only fires on attacker-supplied JWE tokens.
# In cloudflared's case, JWE input comes from Cloudflare-signed tunnel
# tokens — input origin is Cloudflare, not network-reachable to a remote
# attacker.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb, or 2026-09.
# (Note: this CVE-ID appears in mirror-Gokapi's .trivyignore for a
# different reason — Gokapi's go-jose use was OIDC-gated. Here it's
# vendored in cloudflared. Both waivers stand independently.)
CVE-2026-34986

# CVE-2026-39883 — opentelemetry-go SDK BSD kenv PATH hijacking (HIGH).
# Fix in otel-sdk 1.43.0. Vendored inside cloudflared.
#
# Affected codepath: BSD-specific `kenv` command lookup using $PATH instead
# of an absolute path. Linux containers have no `kenv` binary and the
# affected codepath is dead code on Linux. Our container runs Linux only.
# This finding is a pure platform-mismatch false-positive at runtime —
# Trivy flags the version, but the vulnerable function is never reached.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb, or 2026-09.
CVE-2026-39883

# CVE-2026-29181 — go.opentelemetry.io/otel multi-value `baggage` header
# extraction allocates excessively (HIGH, remote DoS amplification).
# Fix in otel 1.41.0. Vendored inside cloudflared at v1.40.0.
#
# Affected codepath: otel's HTTP propagator parses incoming `baggage`
# headers on a server endpoint. cloudflared in this image runs as the
# tunnel CLIENT — outbound to Cloudflare's edge, not a local HTTP server.
# An attacker can only reach an inbound baggage parser by compromising
# Cloudflare's edge first, which is outside our threat model. The
# in-container `cloudflared metrics` HTTP server is bound to a Unix
# socket / localhost only, reachable only by the in-container `node` UID.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb, or 2026-09.
CVE-2026-29181

# CVE-2026-33811, CVE-2026-33814, CVE-2026-39820, CVE-2026-39836, CVE-2026-42499
# — Go stdlib DoS family, this time vendored in cloudflared at Go 1.26.2.
# Fix: stdlib >= 1.25.10 / 1.26.3.
#
# Background — why this is a separate waiver block from the 25679/32280/...
# group above: between 2026-05-03 (uptime-kuma 2.3.2 release) and 2026-05-20
# Cloudflare republished cloudflared with a fresh Go toolchain, jumping
# 1.24.13 -> 1.26.2. That cleared the four 1.24.13 DoS CVEs (which is why
# they have not regressed) but exposed five new 1.26.2 stdlib CVEs that
# weren't yet known when Cloudflare cut the package. Same library, same
# binary path (/usr/bin/cloudflared), same reachability story as the
# 1.24.13 waiver block — just chasing a moving Go-version target. The
# 1.24.13 CVE IDs above stay listed for audit-trail continuity (deleting
# them would erase the history that those CVEs were ever waived, and
# Trivy ignores already-cleared IDs harmlessly).
#
# Per-CVE shape:
#   - CVE-2026-33811 (HIGH) — LookupCNAME with cgo DNS resolver: a very
#     long CNAME response causes resource exhaustion in the resolver.
#   - CVE-2026-33814 (HIGH) — HTTP/2 SETTINGS frame handling enters an
#     infinite loop on a crafted frame, hanging the transport.
#   - CVE-2026-39820 (HIGH) — net/mail ParseAddress*/ParseAddressList
#     pathological inputs cause DoS.
#   - CVE-2026-39836 (HIGH) — Windows-only panic in Dial/LookupPort on
#     NUL bytes in net inputs. Our container runs Linux — the panic path
#     is platform-gated dead code here. Listed anyway for completeness.
#   - CVE-2026-42499 (HIGH) — pathological inputs to net/mail
#     consumePhrase cause DoS during header parsing.
#
# Reachability in our deployment is identical to the 1.24.13 block above
# and the otel/grpc waivers below:
#   1. cloudflared sits idle unless a Cloudflare Tunnel monitor is
#      explicitly configured in uptime-kuma's UI — we don't run one in
#      any deployment of this image.
#   2. Even when active, cloudflared connects as a CLIENT to Cloudflare's
#      edge. The DoS-class inputs would need to come from a Cloudflare-
#      edge compromise, outside our threat model.
#   3. CVE-2026-39836 is platform-gated to Windows; not reachable on
#      Linux containers regardless of monitor configuration.
#
# Cloudflare can't bump Go faster than upstream Go cuts patch releases;
# 1.26.3 landed 2026-05-19 and will reach pkg.cloudflare.com in a fresh
# .deb on Cloudflare's usual ~few-weeks cadence. Until then, these are
# version-match findings without a code path that an attacker reaches.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb (typically every
# few weeks; check pkg.cloudflare.com), or 2026-09 — whichever first.
CVE-2026-33811
CVE-2026-33814
CVE-2026-39820
CVE-2026-39836
CVE-2026-42499

# CVE-2026-39822 (HIGH) — Go stdlib os.Root symlink-following directory
# traversal, vendored in cloudflared, now at Go 1.26.4.
# Fix: stdlib >= 1.25.12 / 1.26.5 / 1.27.0-rc.2.
#
# Continuation of the moving-Go-version target above: Cloudflare has since
# republished cloudflared jumping 1.26.2 -> 1.26.4. That cleared nothing
# relevant here but exposed CVE-2026-39822, disclosed after the 1.26.4
# .deb was cut. Same binary path (/usr/bin/cloudflared), same reachability
# story as every cloudflared Go-stdlib waiver above.
#
# NOTE — this CVE ID ALSO applied to OUR stage-1 healthcheck binary, which
# we build ourselves. That occurrence is FIXED, not waived: GOLANG_BASE was
# bumped 1.26.4 -> 1.26.5-bookworm (see dockerfiles/Dockerfile.override).
# This waiver therefore covers only the cloudflared-vendored copy, which we
# can't bump without Cloudflare rebuilding the .deb. A single .trivyignore
# line can't scope by binary, so it mutes both — acceptable because our own
# occurrence is remediated at the source and can't regress below 1.26.5
# without an override change that would surface in review.
#
# Reachability: os.Root traversal requires an os.Root call reached with an
# attacker-controlled path. cloudflared's filesystem operations run on
# operator- and config-supplied paths (config, certs, logs), never on
# network-reachable input. As with the 1.24.13 / 1.26.2 blocks:
#   1. cloudflared sits idle unless a Cloudflare Tunnel monitor is
#      explicitly configured — we run none in any deployment of this image.
#   2. Even when active, cloudflared is a CLIENT to Cloudflare's edge; a
#      malicious path would require a Cloudflare-edge compromise, outside
#      our threat model.
# Version-match finding without an attacker-reachable code path.
#
# Revisit when Cloudflare ships a fresh cloudflared .deb (typically every
# few weeks; check pkg.cloudflare.com), or 2026-09 — whichever first.
CVE-2026-39822

# ============================================================================
# npm-layer findings — @grpc/grpc-js (uptime-kuma's package-lock.json)
# ============================================================================
# @grpc/grpc-js 1.8.22, fixed in 1.9.16 / 1.10.12 / 1.11.4 / 1.12.7 / 1.13.5 /
# 1.14.4. Transitive runtime dependency present in the image's node_modules.
# Bumping it is upstream's call — we mirror louislam's lockfile verbatim and
# do not override npm versions (same policy as the rest of this file). Both
# are DoS-only (process crash); neither yields code execution or data access.
# Revisit when louislam bumps @grpc/grpc-js (next uptime-kuma release that
# touches the lockfile), or by 2026-11 — whichever first.

# CVE-2026-48068 — "a malformed request can cause a server crash."
# Server-side sink. uptime-kuma uses grpc-js only as a CLIENT (the gRPC
# monitor dials out to a user-configured endpoint); it does not operate a
# gRPC server, so the vulnerable server code path is not present.
CVE-2026-48068

# CVE-2026-48069 — "an incoming malformed compressed message can cause a
# client or server crash." Client path is reachable only if an operator
# configures a gRPC monitor pointing at a hostile/malfunctioning endpoint
# that returns a malformed compressed message — operator-controlled,
# self-inflicted DoS of the monitoring process. Not exposed to untrusted
# inbound traffic.
CVE-2026-48069

# ============================================================================
# 2.4.0 rescan wave (2026-07) — npm-layer findings surfaced by the CVE
# database advancing after the image was built. The chromium fraction of the
# same rescan (all CRITICALs + most HIGHs) is NOT waived: it clears on a
# rebuild because Debian bookworm now ships chromium 150.0.7871.100-1~deb12u1,
# above every fix floor. Only the npm-layer CVEs below need waivers — they are
# pinned in uptime-kuma's package-lock.json@2.4.0 and a same-tag rebuild
# re-resolves the same versions (fix floors sit outside the tilde ranges), so
# they close only on an upstream uptime-kuma release. Same "build-system fork
# only, no source-code fork" invariant as the protobufjs/liquidjs blocks above.
# ============================================================================

# CVE-2026-48712 — protobufjs Denial of Service via uncontrolled recursion
# with a crafted protobuf payload (HIGH). Fix in protobufjs 7.6.1 / 8.4.1.
# uptime-kuma 2.4.0 pins `"protobufjs": "~7.2.6"` directly; installed 7.2.6.
# The tilde range keeps a rebuild on 7.2.x, so this is NOT rebuild-closable.
#
# Same library, same single call site, same reachability story as the
# CVE-2026-41242 / 44289–44293 protobufjs block above: server/monitor-types/
# grpc.js loads a user-supplied .proto and decodes gRPC responses against it.
# The recursion-DoS fires on decode() of attacker-shaped wire bytes — gRPC
# monitor active. We do NOT use the gRPC monitor type in any deployment of
# this image; grpc.js sits in the require graph but its decode path is never
# invoked. DoS only (event-loop stall of the monitoring process).
#
# Revisit triggers (any one reverts the waiver):
#   1. A gRPC monitor is added to any instance running this image — revert.
#   2. louislam bumps protobufjs to >= 7.6.1 — clears this together with the
#      41242 / 44289–44293 block.
#   3. Calendar fallback: 2026-11.
CVE-2026-48712

# CVE-2026-12151 — undici Denial of Service due to unbounded memory growth
# via WebSocket frames (HIGH). Fix in undici 6.27.0 / 7.28.0 / 8.5.0.
# uptime-kuma 2.4.0 pulls undici 6.26.0 into the runtime image transitively
# via exactly one prod path: node_modules/cheerio/node_modules/undici. (The
# other two copies in the lockfile — 7.26.0 via testcontainers, 5.29.0
# top-level — are dev=true and pruned by `npm prune --omit=dev`.)
#
# Exploit prerequisite: the application opens an undici WebSocket client to
# an attacker-controlled server that then streams frames to exhaust memory.
# cheerio uses undici only for its optional load-from-URL fetch helper;
# uptime-kuma feeds cheerio already-fetched HTML strings (keyword monitor),
# never a URL, so cheerio's undici path — and thus the WebSocket client — is
# never invoked. The vulnerable code is present but statically unreachable
# from any uptime-kuma call site. DoS only.
#
# Revisit when louislam / cheerio bump undici to >= 6.27.0, or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-12151

# CVE-2026-52746 — jsonata resource exhaustion via malicious inputs to the
# "$toMillis" function (HIGH, DoS). Fix in jsonata 2.2.0. uptime-kuma 2.4.0
# pins `"jsonata": "~2.1.0"` directly; installed 2.1.1. Fix 2.2.0 is outside
# the tilde range, so NOT rebuild-closable — needs an upstream bump.
#
# Reachability: jsonata backs the json-query monitor type — it evaluates a
# JSONata expression against a monitored endpoint's JSON response. The
# expression itself (where "$toMillis" would be written) is admin-supplied
# via the authenticated monitor-config UI; only the evaluated *data* comes
# from the probe target. Triggering the resource exhaustion requires the
# operator to author a pathological expression, or attacker-influenced data
# to reach a $toMillis call inside an operator-written expression. Worst case
# is a transient event-loop stall of the monitoring process — DoS only, no
# RCE or privilege-boundary crossing.
#
# Revisit when louislam bumps jsonata to >= 2.2.0, or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-52746

# GHSA-p6gq-j5cr-w38f — nodemailer message-level `raw` option bypasses
# disableFileAccess / disableUrlAccess, enabling arbitrary file/URL access
# (HIGH). Fix in nodemailer 9.0.1. uptime-kuma 2.4.0 pins `"nodemailer":
# "~7.0.13"` directly; installed 7.0.13. Fix 9.0.1 is two majors out, so NOT
# rebuild-closable — needs an upstream bump.
#
# Reachability: nodemailer is the SMTP notification provider. The bypass
# requires the caller to set the message-level `raw` option with attacker-
# controlled content. uptime-kuma's smtp provider constructs the message from
# admin-configured notification settings (subject/body/recipients) and does
# not expose the `raw` option to external/probe input. Reaching the bug needs
# an operator to craft a malicious `raw` message via the authenticated
# notification-config UI — an escalation from an already-authenticated admin,
# not a new privilege boundary for a remote attacker.
#
# Revisit when louislam bumps nodemailer to >= 9.0.1, or 2026-11.
GHSA-p6gq-j5cr-w38f

# CVE-2026-12143 — form-data form-field override via CRLF injection (HIGH).
# Fix in form-data 4.0.6 (also 2.5.6 / 3.0.5). uptime-kuma 2.4.0 pins
# `"form-data": "~4.0.5"` directly; installed 4.0.5. Although 4.0.6 is inside
# the `~4.0.5` range, `npm ci` installs the lockfile-pinned 4.0.5 verbatim, so
# a same-tag rebuild does NOT pick it up — closable only when louislam
# refreshes the lockfile.
#
# Exploit prerequisite: an attacker must control a multipart field name or
# filename that uptime-kuma passes into a form-data body, letting injected
# CRLF sequences forge additional multipart fields in an OUTBOUND request.
# uptime-kuma builds multipart bodies only in notification/monitor code with
# field names hardcoded by the provider; no external/probe input flows into a
# form-data field name. Integrity of an outbound request at worst, not a
# server-side compromise.
#
# Revisit when louislam refreshes the lockfile to form-data >= 4.0.6, or
# 2026-11.
CVE-2026-12143

# CVE-2026-48815 — sigstore `certificateOIDs` verification constraints are
# silently dropped and never enforced (HIGH). Fix in sigstore 4.1.1.
#
# NOTE: sigstore is NOT a uptime-kuma dependency — it does not appear in
# uptime-kuma's package-lock.json at all. Trivy flags it because npm itself
# bundles `sigstore` (for package-provenance verification) inside the
# node:22-bookworm-slim base image at /usr/local/lib/node_modules/npm/. Our
# container runs `node server/server.js` and never executes `npm install`, so
# the sigstore verification code is never reached at runtime — it is npm
# tooling that sits dormant in the image.
#
# This is closable two ways, neither being the source rebuild: (a) a NODE_BASE
# digest bump to a node:22-bookworm-slim that bundles npm with sigstore
# >= 4.1.1 (Renovate territory, pinDigests), or (b) this waiver. Waived for
# now because it is runtime-unreachable; will clear naturally on the next
# NODE_BASE bump.
#
# Revisit on the next NODE_BASE digest bump, or 2026-11.
CVE-2026-48815

# CVE-2026-48779 — ws Denial of Service via memory exhaustion from small
# WebSocket fragments (HIGH). Fix in ws 8.21.0 (also 5.2.5 / 6.2.4 / 7.5.11).
# uptime-kuma 2.4.0 carries ws in the runtime image as: 8.19.0 (direct,
# `"ws": "~8.19.0"`), 8.20.1 (via engine.io / engine.io-client /
# socket.io-adapter — the socket.io transport), and 7.5.11 (via mqtt). All
# below the 8.21.0 fix; the tilde/transitive pins keep a rebuild below it, so
# NOT rebuild-closable — needs an upstream bump.
#
# Honest exposure — unlike the other entries in this wave, this one IS
# network-reachable pre-auth: the 8.20.1 copies back socket.io, i.e. the
# uptime-kuma dashboard's real-time WebSocket channel. A client can open that
# socket before authenticating and stream tiny fragments to grow server
# memory. So the "admin-gated" argument does NOT apply here.
#
# Why we accept the risk for THIS deployment:
#  1. Impact is memory-exhaustion DoS only — the process may be OOM-killed and
#     restarted by the container runtime. No RCE, no data access, no
#     privilege-boundary crossing.
#  2. Same posture as the liquidjs CVE-2026-45618 acceptance above: this
#     image's dashboard is not exposed to untrusted networks — it runs on our
#     internal segment behind network controls, so the pre-auth socket is not
#     reachable by arbitrary remote clients.
#  3. mqtt's 7.5.11 copy is a monitor-side WebSocket *client* (self-inflicted
#     only), not an inbound server surface.
#
# Revisit triggers (any one reverts the waiver):
#  1. This image's dashboard becomes reachable from an untrusted network —
#     revert; the containment that this waiver rests on is then gone.
#  2. louislam bumps ws / socket.io to pull ws >= 8.21.0 — clear and rebuild.
#  3. Calendar fallback: 2026-11.
CVE-2026-48779
